The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Thursday, July 07, 2005 

 BRIEFS

 Purulia, July 6: A Class VII student was killed this morning after a classmate punched him behind his ear following a quarrel over who would sit on the back bench. 

 Biswajit Mahato and Rahin Mahali of Sri Aurobindo High School at Dukuri in Purulia, 280 km from Calcutta, had entered their classroom after the morning prayer when they began fighting over the seat. Rahin hit Biswajit behind his ear and he fell unconscious. He was rushed to hospital where he was declared dead on arrival.

 Calcutta: The Trinamul Congress will boycott Thursdays oath-taking ceremony in which CPM councillors Biswajiban Majumdar and Ila Nandy will be sworn in as chairperson and vice-chairperson of the Bidhannagar municipality. The Trinamul councillors have decided to stay away to protest against alleged rigging by the CPM in the June 19 civic polls. 

 Krishnagar: Around 1,000 people were rendered homeless on Tuesday night following erosion on the banks of the Bhagirathi in Nabadwip town. The erosion wiped out nearly 15,000 sq ft of the riverbank, including agricultural land.

 Behrampore: A 21-year-old pregnant woman was allegedly throttled to death and thrown off a bridge into a canal by her husband for bringing charges of torture against him at a Murshidabad village. The husband is absconding.

 Calcutta: Twenty-one top-notch consultants, including Price Waterhouse Coopers, Earnest amp; Young and Tata Consultancy Services, have responded to the state power departments expression of interest, a 90-day study into ways of making the West Bengal State Electricity Board, Durgapur Projects Limited and the West Bengal Power Development Corporation economically viable and bettering their quality of service.

 Behrampore: A 47-year-old woman was killed and three persons injured in a clash at a religious function in Jagaipur village under Naoda police station on Wednesday. Usha Rani Rakshit was hit in her head with brickbats.




